  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30_1",
    "text": "Figure 1.4.1.1: DoD Risk Model. (\"DoD Risk Model\" by Unknown, U.S. Naval Academy - Cyber Science Dept is in the Public Domain, CCO)",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.1277842408581161,
      0.4273255816063734,
      0.8740601372719623,
      0.45219011254394176
    ],
    "page": "jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30",
    "order": 12
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30_10",
    "text": "In the cyber domain, just as in all domains, there are various factors that go into assessing risk. Risk Assessment can be viewed as a function with inputs, a process, and outputs. In general risk is viewed as a function of likelihood of occurrence of an event and impact of an event, risk( likelihood, impact ) .",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.08458645580357173,
      0.45930232559189627,
      0.9154135476503754,
      0.5058139529876505
    ],
    "page": "jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30",
    "order": 13
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30_11",
    "text": "Intuitively, if we increase the likelihood of a negative event occurring, the risk severity increases, and vice versa. This is also the case with impact, if the impact of a negative event occurring increases, the risk severity increases.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.08458647441605593,
      0.5145348840773037,
      0.9154135532781789,
      0.5436507934987777
    ],
    "page": "jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30",
    "order": 14
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30_12",
    "text": "Likelihood of Occurrence",
    "canon_role": "section_header",
    "bbox": [
      0.08646616968420241,
      0.5566860466270855,
      0.26315789341103574,
      0.566964285763736
    ],
    "page": "jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30",
    "order": 15
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30_13",
    "text": "Likelihood of occurrence can be decomposed into two main components: threat and vulnerability. Threat is any circumstance or event that has the potential to adversely impact our system. Threat can be adversarial (purposely caused by a person) or nonadversarial (caused by an accident or natural event such as a hurricane). Vulnerability represents a weakness in an information system that can be exploited, often by an adversarial threat actor.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.08458645234962463,
      0.5770348836224195,
      0.9154135476503754,
      0.6381448411822317
    ],
    "page": "jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30",
    "order": 16
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30_14",
    "text": "Not all vulnerabilities are equal, there are factors that we can assess a vulnerability with. The risk assessment team will ask and answer questions such as (OWASP):",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.08458646609710972,
      0.6468023256100649,
      0.9135338207193147,
      0.6758720930299229
    ],
    "page": "jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30",
    "order": 17
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30_15",
    "text": "(Discoverable) How easy is it for an adversary to discover the vulnerability?",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.08646615623220391,
      0.6845238094198451,
      0.5883458666732742,
      0.6991567459277817
    ],
    "page": "jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30",
    "order": 18
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30_16",
    "text": "(Exploitable) How easy is it for an adversary to exploit the vulnerability?",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.08646617258079467,
      0.7005813957405471,
      0.569548856961812,
      0.7151162788234063
    ],
    "page": "jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30",
    "order": 19
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30_17",
    "text": "(Awareness) How well known is the vulnerability?",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.08834587347241475,
      0.7180059522001984,
      0.42857142618923927,
      0.7296626982319443
    ],
    "page": "jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30",
    "order": 20
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30_18",
    "text": "(Detectable) How likely is an exploit to be detected?",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.08834588114909016,
      0.7311046512395781,
      0.4398496181616865,
      0.7456395343224373
    ],
    "page": "jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30",
    "order": 21
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30_19",
    "text": "Just as vulnerabilities, threats are also assessed using various factors. The risk assessment team will ask and answer questions such as (OWASP):",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.08270674739727568,
      0.7557043650494948,
      0.9154135367004689,
      0.7834821429149822
    ],
    "page": "jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30",
    "order": 22
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30_20",
    "text": "(Capability) How technically skilled is an adversary?",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.08834586886748115,
      0.7936046509552683,
      0.443609026762218,
      0.806795634735115
    ],
    "page": "jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30",
    "order": 23
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30_21",
    "text": "(Capability) How much does the adversary know about the target system?",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.08646616889097739,
      0.809523809726785,
      0.5733082741541353,
      0.8241567462347215
    ],
    "page": "jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30",
    "order": 24
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30_22",
    "text": "(Opportunity) Does the adversary have the resources (technology) to exploit a vulnerability?",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.08646617531989065,
      0.8255813949913693,
      0.6898496227735571,
      0.8415697676124513
    ],
    "page": "jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30",
    "order": 25
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30_23",
    "text": "(Opportunity) Is the adversary in a position to exploit a vulnerability?",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.08646618402878138,
      0.8415178572025976,
      0.5488721710840004,
      0.8561507937105342
    ],
    "page": "jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30",
    "order": 26
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30_24",
    "text": "(Intent) How motivated is an adversary to find and exploit a vulnerability?",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.08646616890223136,
      0.8575581399411286,
      0.5770676558722049,
      0.8720930230239877
    ],
    "page": "jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30",
    "order": 27
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30_25",
    "text": "(Intent) Does the actor performing the exploit intend harm?",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.08834586795112774,
      0.8735119048531376,
      0.4830827100563909,
      0.8866567461229788
    ],
    "page": "jiaocaineedrop_eng-45646.pdf_30",
    "order": 28
  },
